      <!-- Medical Disclaimer -->
      <div class="disclaimer">
        <div class="disclaimer-title">Medical Disclaimer</div>
        <p>This calculator provides general estimates based on IOM (Institute of Medicine) guidelines and is not a substitute for professional medical advice. Every pregnancy is unique. Your healthcare provider may recommend different weight gain targets based on your individual health, medical history, and pregnancy complications. Always consult your doctor or midwife for personalized guidance.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- SEO Content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>How Much Weight Should You Gain During Pregnancy?</h2>
        <p>Pregnancy weight gain is one of the most common concerns for expectant mothers. Gaining the right amount of weight supports your baby's healthy development while reducing your risk of pregnancy complications. The Institute of Medicine (IOM) provides evidence-based guidelines based on your pre-pregnancy Body Mass Index (BMI).</p>

        <h3>Why Pre-Pregnancy BMI Matters</h3>
        <p>Your BMI before pregnancy is the primary factor in determining how much weight you should gain. BMI is calculated by dividing your weight in kilograms by your height in meters squared. Women who start pregnancy underweight need to gain more weight to ensure adequate nutrition for the baby, while women who start at a higher BMI are advised to gain less to reduce risks of gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, and cesarean delivery.</p>

        <h3>First Trimester Weight Gain</h3>
        <p>During the first trimester (weeks 1&ndash;12), weight gain is minimal &mdash; typically 1 to 5 pounds total regardless of BMI category. Some women even lose weight due to morning sickness, which is usually not a concern unless the loss is significant. The baby is very small during this period, and most caloric needs can be met by eating a normal, balanced diet without extra calories.</p>

        <h3>Second and Third Trimester Weight Gain</h3>
        <p>The majority of pregnancy weight gain occurs during the second and third trimesters when the baby is growing rapidly. During these weeks, steady, gradual weight gain is ideal. For normal-weight women, this means gaining about 1 pound per week. The rate varies by BMI category &mdash; underweight women should aim for slightly more, while overweight and obese women should aim for less.</p>

        <h3>Risks of Too Little or Too Much Weight Gain</h3>
        <p>Gaining too little weight during pregnancy increases the risk of delivering a low birth weight baby (under 5.5 lbs), preterm birth, and developmental delays. Gaining too much weight raises the risk of gestational diabetes, high blood pressure, preeclampsia, cesarean delivery, macrosomia (a larger-than-average baby), and difficulty losing weight after pregnancy.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Too little gain:</strong> Low birth weight, preterm delivery, nutrient deficiencies</li>
          <li><strong>Too much gain:</strong> Gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, macrosomia, difficult labor</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Tips for Healthy Pregnancy Weight Gain</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Eat nutrient-dense foods &mdash; focus on fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, whole grains, and dairy</li>
          <li>You only need about 340 extra calories per day in the 2nd trimester and 450 in the 3rd trimester</li>
          <li>Stay active &mdash; most pregnant women can safely walk, swim, or do prenatal yoga</li>
          <li>Weigh yourself weekly at the same time of day for consistent tracking</li>
          <li>Talk to your healthcare provider if your weight gain is significantly above or below the recommended range</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">How much weight should I gain during pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Weight gain depends on your pre-pregnancy BMI. The IOM recommends 28&ndash;40 lbs for underweight women (BMI &lt; 18.5), 25&ndash;35 lbs for normal weight (BMI 18.5&ndash;24.9), 15&ndash;25 lbs for overweight (BMI 25&ndash;29.9), and 11&ndash;20 lbs for obese women (BMI &ge; 30). These ranges are for single pregnancies; twin pregnancies require more.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">How is pregnancy weight gain distributed?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Pregnancy weight gain is distributed across the baby (7&ndash;8 lbs), placenta (1&ndash;2 lbs), amniotic fluid (2 lbs), uterine growth (2 lbs), breast tissue (1&ndash;3 lbs), increased blood volume (3&ndash;4 lbs), body fluids (2&ndash;3 lbs), and maternal fat stores (6&ndash;8 lbs). The total adds up to approximately 25&ndash;35 lbs for a normal-weight woman.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">When do you gain the most weight during pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Most weight gain occurs in the second and third trimesters. In the first trimester, you typically gain only 1&ndash;5 lbs total. During the second and third trimesters, you can expect to gain about 1 lb per week for normal-weight women. The baby gains the most weight in the third trimester, adding about half a pound per week.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">Is it normal to lose weight in the first trimester?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes, mild weight loss in the first trimester is common and usually not a concern, especially if caused by morning sickness or food aversions. Most women regain this weight and more during the second trimester. However, if you lose more than 5% of your pre-pregnancy weight, or if nausea and vomiting are severe, talk to your healthcare provider.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">What if I'm gaining too much or too little weight?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">If your weight gain falls outside the recommended range, discuss it with your healthcare provider. They can help adjust your nutrition plan and check for underlying issues. Excessive gain increases risk of gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, and cesarean delivery. Insufficient gain may lead to preterm birth or low birth weight. Small adjustments to diet and activity can often bring weight gain back on track.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">How does BMI affect pregnancy weight gain recommendations?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Pre-pregnancy BMI is the primary factor because it reflects your nutritional reserves. Women with lower BMIs need to gain more weight to provide adequate energy and nutrients. Women with higher BMIs already have greater energy reserves, so they need less additional gain and face higher risks from excessive gain. The IOM guidelines are based on large population studies linking BMI-specific weight gain to optimal outcomes.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">How much weight should I gain per week during pregnancy?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">After the first trimester, recommended weekly gain is: underweight women about 1.0&ndash;1.3 lbs per week, normal weight about 0.8&ndash;1.0 lb per week, overweight about 0.5&ndash;0.7 lbs per week, and obese women about 0.4&ndash;0.6 lbs per week. First trimester gain is typically just 1&ndash;5 lbs total, so there's no set weekly target during that period.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">Does pregnancy weight gain recommendation change for twins?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes, weight gain recommendations are higher for twin pregnancies. The IOM recommends 37&ndash;54 lbs for normal weight, 31&ndash;50 lbs for overweight, and 25&ndash;42 lbs for obese women carrying twins. Adequate weight gain with twins is especially important since twins are often born earlier and need sufficient growth in utero. No specific guidelines exist for underweight women with twins, so work closely with your provider.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

